<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environmental Audit Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Paul Appleby CEng FCIBSE FRSA – Consultant in Sustainable Design</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It appears to me that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Government’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> document on the Housing Standards Review</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">demonstrates a lack of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">understand</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the Code for Sustainable Homes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (CSH)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. For a start </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">energy and carbon emissions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is only one of a wide range of criteria assessed under the Code</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Although this is reflected elsewhere in the document the section dealing with energy gives the impression that CSH is to be abandoned completely. This has also been the consensus of the associated press coverage. Secondly CSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is not a standard as such but an assessment protocol, designed to assess the overall sustainability of a dwelling. Thirdly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, with regard to energy,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the Consultation refers to an early version of the Code that compares</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> dwelling emission rate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DER</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> levels against 2006 targets, wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ereas the 2010 edition uses Approved Document (AD)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 2010. Lastly the whole idea behind both CSH and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Building Research Establishment Environmental Assessment Method</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">BREEAM</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) from which it evolved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is to promote design and construction that go beyond Building Reg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ulation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s and standard practice. I very much hope that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t is not the Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tention to scrap CSH entirely. In my view </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the energy credits</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be revise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d in line with revisions in AD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> - which was always BRE's intention.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> I would strongly recommend disconnecting CSH from Government regulation and reverting to its original manifestation as an environmental assessment scheme administered by BRE.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a freelance consultant I specialise in the sustainable design of buildings and providing advice to design and masterplanning teams on all aspects of sustainability. I graduated with a first class honours degree in Environmental Engineering in 1975 since when I have worked as a mechanical services design engineer, a lecturer and researcher, setting up my own consultancy in 1988. This became Building Health Consultants Ltd, which remains today as part of URS Scott Wilson. In 2000 I established the Building Sustainability Unit at URS, from which I retired at the end of 2008.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I am a Cabe Built Environment Expert, involved primarily with the Design Review of schemes in the planning process. I am an active member of the UK Green Building Council, involved in a task group that recently published a report on alternative incentives for the Green Deal.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I have some 60 publications to my name including the books </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Integrated Sustainable Design of Buildings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which was published in 2011 by Earthscan; and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Sustainable Retrofit and Facilities Management</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, published by Earthscan in 2013. These are comprehensive guides to sustainable design, masterplanning and construction, and the operation and refurbishment of existing buildings respectively: both intended for a global marketplace, but with a particular focus on the UK.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Code for Sustainable Homes evolved from EcoHomes, which in turn evolved from the Building Research Establishment Environmental Assessment Method (BREEAM), which appeared originally in 1990 as a scheme for rating the predicted environmental performance of offices. None of these schemes were intended to replace Building Regulations nor to set legally enforceable standards. The aim was always to reward building designs that exceeded current regulations and norms. As a spin-off from this some of the performance criteria were designed to nudge legislators into improving performance standards. One example of this was the ‘Credits’ awarded for reduction in dwelling emission rates (DER) established as part of the Code for Sustainable Homes: one credit corresponding to a 8% reduction in predicted CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> emissions compared with the target emission rate (TER) set in Part L1A of the Building Regulations; up to 10 credits for a predicted ‘net zero carbon home’.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is confirmed in the preface to the 2010 version as follows:</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">‘The Code for Sustainable Homes (CSH) is an environmental assessment method for rating and certifying the performance of new homes. It is a national standard for use in the design and construction of new homes with a view to encouraging continuous improvement in sustainable home building.’</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Although in my view the use of the term ‘standard’ in this context could be misconstrued, since I do not believe that an assessment scheme should be used as a standard, rather than as a means of testing a building against norms or regulations and rewarding those elements that exceed normal or required practice. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I note that the section in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Housing Standards Review (HSR)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Consultation document dealing with Water Efficiency discusses the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> CSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> requirements without recommending their being dropped.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Indeed it recognizes that where there is a ‘clear local need’, e.g. local water shortages, the ‘Code Level 3’ criterion may be applied; which specifies a water consumption that is 15 litres/s per person per year lower than Part G of Building Regulations.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CSH requirements are also referred to in the context of daylighting and materials, although in neither case is it recommended that they be incorporated into Housing Standards going forward.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One cross-cutting issue that is referred to in the HSR Consultation but not in CSH is that of over-heating in homes. There is evidence that overheating of dwellings is not uncommon, particularly in towns and cities in the south of England. The risk factors are well known: exposure to solar and other heat gains, inadequate opportunities to ventilate naturally, prolonged high outdoor temperatures, particularly at night, and fabric that prevents heat escaping, for example. Current Building Regulations include an estimate of overheating risk in the SAP calculations required for Part L compliance and a requirement to be able to purge heat to comply with Part F.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Overheating can lead to extreme discomfort, heat stress and ultimately to death. However there is no epidemiological evidence that correlates indoor temperatures in dwellings to mortality rates. The statistics available show the relationship between outdoor temperature and deaths: indicating that as average outdoor </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">temperatures over two days exceed 24.7˚C mortality starts to increase, perhaps doubling at around 35˚C.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Because of predicted climate change impacts and consequent increases in summertime temperatures, along with increased occupancy densities and heat islands in cities, there is a risk that incidences of overheating will increase. In higher spec new apartments this is already leading to the installation of air conditioning, or its retrofit in existing apartments. This clearly has escalating energy and carbon implications. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are also a number of CSH issues that are not referred to at all in the HSR Consultation. Specifically: Sound Insulation, global warming potential (GWP) of insulants, NO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">x</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> emissions, surface water and flood risk, and ecology.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sound insulation is a surprising omission since it is currently covered by Approved Document E of the Building Regulations and CSH rewards improvements on the airborne and impact sound insulation values specified therein. These enhancements have significant impact on party floor and wall composition and associated performance and cost. Sound transmission between neighbouring dwellings can be a major cause of tension and I would have thought that the Government would take this opportunity to review this standard.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GWP of insulants should strictly be considered under the heading of ‘materials impacts’, but in turn is an important element in the whole life greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions assessment of dwellings. Some would argue that decisions on insulation, environmental services and renewable energy strategies should be based on whole life GHG or carbon dioxide equivalent emissions. In this context it seems odd that there is no reference to the Passivhaus standard, which is gaining popularity as a framework for designing low energy buildings. With low operational carbon emissions embodied emissions become the greater influence on life cycle carbon performance.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">x</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> emissions are contingent on type of heating fuel, combustion efficiency and flue arrangement. They are therefore intimately tied in with the energy/carbon assessment and renewables strategy. For example use of a biomass boiler can significantly reduce dwelling CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> emissions but fail to meet the criteria for credits under the NO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">x</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> heading in a CSH assessment. Housing Standards may not be a suitable vehicle for nudging the demand for biomass one way or the other however.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Surface water and flood risk are currently not within the scope of Building Regulations, but are covered by the planning process.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ecological impact associated with housing development is not governed by any current standards or legislation beyond that controlling development on green belt land or where land is designated with environmental protection, such as a Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI).</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">3.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I do not believe that the Code for Sustainable Homes should ever have been brought under the auspices of the Department for Communities &amp; Local Government, since there has always been this confusion between regulatory requirements and a CSH assessment outcome. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In my view CSH should be retained under the control of BRE alongside its BREEAM suite of assessment schemes, updated periodically as Building Regulations and technical advances demand. Perhaps CSH should revert back to its EcoHomes incarnation, whilst also incorporating the transport-related credits that were dropped when it became CSH. I would consider that this is in line with the HSR’s commitment to ‘wind down the role of the Code’ (para 40).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As Building Regulations demand lower operational carbon targets embodied carbon will become more critical in life cycle carbon performance. In my view future standards should factor in embodied carbon and more attention should be focussed on the embodied carbon of building products and the impact they have on whole life carbon.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In my view the Consultation does not give sufficient weight to the issue of overheating in dwellings. I think that this is an increasing problem, particularly in towns and cities in the south of England. It is also likely to increase the installation of air conditioning, which as heating energy use reduces will start to dominate annual carbon emissions. The method for determining cooling energy consumption currently incorporated into SAP is much simplified, based as it is primarily on the balance between solar gain and free cooling</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for 3 months of the year and 6 hours a day.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">1 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>